      "content": "I can see how that might feel, but rest assured, there aren't any hidden factors actively working against you. The feeling you're experiencing is due to the nature of how interest is calculated and applied to your loan. As I mentioned earlier, the interest is calculated on the remaining principal balance, which decreases as you make payments. This means that the amount of interest you're paying each month will also decrease over time, making it feel like the debt is resisting your payments at first.\n\nHowever, once you continue making payments and the principal balance decreases, the interest will decrease at a slower rate, giving you a sense of progress and making it easier to pay off the debt. It's like a roller coaster ride; initially, the drops (interest) seem steep, but as you ride higher (pay off the principal), the drops become less intense, making the ride smoother.\n\nRemember, it's important to stay focused on your goal and keep making regular payments. With time, you'll see the principal balance decrease, and the interest will become less of a burden. Keep up the good work, and you'll eventually pay off your student loan!",
